      <div xml:id="NA147-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi colliyatu. (ETv: pakalē ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi paraittumoḻi kiḷaviyāl varaivu kaṭāyatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said while [HE] was behind the fence. (ETv: How the confidante urged for marriage by means of a speaking a ??? word while [HE] was behind the fence during day time.)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA147">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            yāṅkā kuvamō vaṇinutaṟ kuṟumaka</l>
<l>            ṭēmpaṭu cāraṟ ciṟutiṉaip peruṅkural</l>
<l>            cevvāyp paiṅkiḷi kavara nīmaṟ</l>
<l>            ṟevvāyc ceṉṟaṉai yavaṇeṉak kūṟi</l>
<l>            yaṉṉai yāṉāḷ kaḻaṟa muṉṉiṉ </l>
<l>            ṟaruvi yārkkum peruvarai nāṭaṉai</l>
<l>            yaṟiyalu maṟiyēṉ kāṇṭalu milaṉē</l>
<l>            vetirpuṉai taṭṭaiyēṉ malarppūk koytu</l>
<l>            cuṉaippāyn tāṭiṟṟu milaṉeṉa niṉaivilai, {kaṉaviṉ}</l>
<l>            poyya lantō vāyttaṉai yatukēṭṭut </l>
<l>            talaiyiṟaiñ ciṉaḷē yaṉṉai</l>
<l>            celavoḻin taṉaiyā laḷiyainī puṉattē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>What will become of us, little woman with decorated forehead ?</l>
<l rend="indent">When mother murmured unendingly(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">āṉāḷ kaḻaṟa</term>: "while she murmured as one who does not end"?</note> and said</l>
<l rend="indent2">“to which place did you go from there,</l>
<l rend="indent2">just you<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nī maṟṟu</term>: exclusive in the sense of "just you among all the others" or with the meaning given in Tol.Col. 257i, namely a change of occupation?</note>, while the red-mouthed green parakeets seized</l>
<l rend="indent2">the big ears of the small millet on the slope rich in honey?”,</l>
<l>you stood in front [of her]</l>
<l rend="indent">{as if in a dream,} [and] did not think<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">niṉaivilai</term> is by T.V.G. not taken as a neg. 2nd sg. (which should not have the neg. infix -<term xml:lang="ta">il</term>), but split as <term xml:lang="ta">niṉaivu ilai</term>. Clear is the ET variant <term xml:lang="ta">niṉaiyilai</term>.</note>, saying</l>
<l rend="indent2">“I don't know at all the man from a land of great mountains</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the waterfalls sound. I have not seen [him] at all.</l>
<l rend="indent2">I had a Taṭṭai fashioned out of bamboo. I did not play<note place="foot">For the type of negation where the perfective neuter singular in -<term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟu</term> (or here <term xml:lang="ta">-iṟṟu</term>) has to be analysed as an verbal noun see note on NA 27. The preceding clause ending in <term xml:lang="ta">kāṇṭalum ilaṉ-ē</term> shows that the two forms were regarded as similar in this particular construction.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">plucking blossoming flowers [and] jumping into mountain pools.”</l>
<l>Don't lie<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">poyyal</term>: T.V.G. wants to read an indicative here in the sense of "you can't lie". But we can take "lie" here in the sense of denial: "don't deny (what you have done, i.e. that you have told mother)".</note>, alas. You have achieved it. Having heard that</l>
<l>mother bent [her] head.</l>
<l>You have [forthwith] ceased going to the fields, pitiable you.</l>
        </lg>
